Sec. 90001. Border infrastructure and wall system.  
Provides a $46.55 billion, FY-2025 appropriation to the U.S. Customs and Border Protection Commissioner for wall construction, access roads, detection technology, and site preparation, all to remain available until September 30, 2029.

Sec. 90002. U.S. Customs and Border Protection personnel, fleet vehicles, and facilities.  
Authorizes $4.1 billion for hiring and training new agents, $2.05 billion for retention bonuses, $855 million for vehicle procurement and repair, and $5 billion for facility construction or leasing, all through September 30, 2029, while barring use of the personnel funds for processing-coordinator hiring after October 31, 2028.

Sec. 90003. Detention capacity.  
Allots $45 billion to U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement for single-adult and family residential detention through September 30, 2029, with family-center standards left to the Secretary of Homeland Security’s discretion.

Sec. 90004. Border security, technology, and screening.  
Appropriates $6.168 billion for CBP to buy AI-enabled inspection equipment, upgrade air/marine platforms, install surveillance tech, deploy biometric exit systems, screen entrants, assist unaccompanied minors, combat fentanyl, and fund commemorative events, all until September 30, 2029, while prohibiting new un-tested surveillance towers.

Sec. 90005. State and local assistance.  
Sets aside $500 million for unmanned-aircraft detection, $625 million for 2026 FIFA World Cup security, $1 billion for 2028 Olympics security, and $450 million for Operation Stonegarden, all through September 30, 2029, plus creates a $10 billion State Border Security Reinforcement Fund available until September 30, 2034, for state and local border-wall construction, ground prep, crime-related interdiction, and alien relocation, with applications accepted within 90 days of enactment.

Sec. 90006. Presidential residence protection.  
Provides $300 million to reimburse state and local law-enforcement costs for protecting any residence of the President designated under the Presidential Protection Assistance Act, covering expenses incurred on or after July 1, 2024, that are demonstrably above normal operations and certified by the Secret Service, with up to 3 percent of the funds reserved for administration.

Sec. 90007. Department of Homeland Security appropriations for border support.  
Allots an additional $10 billion to the Secretary of Homeland Security for border-support activities, available until September 30, 2029.

Sec. 90101. FEHB improvements.  
Establishes the FEHB Protection Act of 2025, requiring the Office of Personnel Management Director to verify qualifying-life-event claims and family-eligibility documentation within one year, conduct a three-year audit of ineligible enrollees, and create a process to disenroll them within 180 days, while appropriating $66 million in FY-2026 for these oversight activities through FY-2035.

Sec. 90102. Pandemic Response Accountability Committee.  
Appropriates $88 million for FY-2026 to fund the Pandemic Response Accountability Committee’s oversight of pandemic-related spending, and extends the expiration date of the CARES Act’s Section 15010 from 2025 to 2034.

Sec. 90103. Appropriation for the Office of Management and Budget.  
Provides $100 million to the Office of Management and Budget for FY-2025 to identify budget and accounting efficiencies across the executive branch, available until September 30, 2029. [end of text]


